\begin_layout Section
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Algorithms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our project uses four different algorithms to solve the meal planning and
 food waste reduction problem.
 Each algorithm takes a unique approach to find an optimal solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Greedy Solver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Greedy Solver makes the best choice at each step without looking ahead.
 It:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Checks available actions (meals that can be made with current ingredients)
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Picks the action with the highest score 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Updates the state and repeats until the goal is reached or no more actions
 are possible
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method is fast but may miss better overall solutions by focusing on
 immediate gains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Planning Graph Solver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This solver builds a graph of possible actions and their outcomes.
 It works in two main steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Build the graph: Starting with the initial ingredients, it adds layers
 of possible meals and the resulting ingredient states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Extract the solution: It works backwards from the goal state, choosing
 the best meals at each step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method can find good solutions for complex problems but may take more
 time for larger datasets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Reinforcement Learning Solver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This solver learns from repeated attempts to solve the problem.
 It uses Q-learning, a type of reinforcement learning.
 The process includes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Trying different actions and observing outcomes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Updating a "Q-table" that stores the expected value of each action in
 each state 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Balancing exploration of new options with using known good choices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solver improves its decisions over many episodes, potentially finding
 clever solutions that other methods might miss.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Simulated Annealing Solver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inspired by the metal annealing process, this solver:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Starts with a random solution 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Makes small changes to the solution 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Accepts improvements always and worse solutions sometimes, based on a
 "temperature" that decreases over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method can escape local optima and find good solutions for complex
 problems.
\end_layout

